I’m not sure if race cars are more beautiful in their simplicity or their complexity. Or maybe their utility, with every part added being done so for performance, yet bringing style in the process. It’s a hard-to-define, but definite vibe. 

Brad Gary ( @brad4g63 )’s Talon, built by @tpg_tuning, hits extra hard for me because it’s been a hometown hero since before I moved from southwestern PA to CA 15 years ago. In all that time, Brad’s Talon has gone from “fast” to “seriously fast,” and has gotten ever better looking all the while. 

I was proud to shoot and write about it all for a recent feature in @superstreet (head over for more!)

#DSM #Talon #EagleTalon #Eclipse #2Geclipse #2gtalon #talontsi #eclipsegsx #turbo #7second #tgptuning

@thehoonigans’s #Gymkhana2022 film launched this morning, and it’s b*o*n*k*e*r*s*

Despite how much of a performance monster this 800+hp, 4WD ‘83 Subaru GL wagon is, when I first shot these I remember thinking how it seemed a little … “fragile” to me. Like a badass SEMA restoration with tons of custom fab that I would NOT want to see get beat up doing Gymkhana things.

But after seeing it 50-50 some K-rails and literally fly at 165mph (and doing everything else it does in the film), this thing is rugged as any proper race machine.

And of course, @travispastrana kills it behind the wheel. 

A star is officially born. Two, really. 👏 

#hoonigan #gymkhana2022 #travispastrana #subaru #SubaruGL #SubaruGLwagon #thefamilyhuckster

In the small handful of times I worked with Ken Block, I would’ve considered him drastically overworked if he were any other man. It always amazed me how he could do so much under a ridiculously crazy travel schedule, and always while he had a million other things going on. 

One of the earliest was during a skit he filmed for Jay Leno’s Garage. IIRC, Ken flew in either that morning or the evening before, and had an early call time on the outskirts of LA. Jay kept a busy schedule for himself, and hanging out on a cold and windy January morning in warm (RE: cold) clothes for hours on end probably wasn’t something any other two men of their caliber would look forward to. But since there were cool cars, fast stunt driving, and each other involved, they seemed like kids on Christmas unwrapping their new go-fast toys together. 

After that long day, Ken was still nice enough to invite us out for food. And despite the entire restaurant staff geeking out over his presence and asking for autographs, he happily obliged, making not only our day but that of everyone who met him, and ultimately, his fans around the world. 

The last time I saw Ken was even crazier. He came straight to Tire Slayer Studios from LAX for a full day of filming, shredded the yard in his Hyundai i20 WRC car, spun a truly insane donut inside the garage (which we thought might be impossible) — all in his first drive there — modeled his new line of clothes, filmed another promo, *and then* stuck around to sign autographs late into the night for a crowd of diehard fans. 

All this reinforced one of the most important lessons I learned from the man: He always showed up and gave it 100. Ken accomplished more in his career and in life than anyone else I can think of, largely by this discipline. And of course, by his unparalleled talents.

I’d encourage anyone to read what’s been written about Ken from the people who knew him best. There’s no shortage of inspiration to draw from the monumental example he set. 🏆

With all the unfortunate vehicles in history that have flopped, become Internet humor, or were scrapped before even coming to production, imagine being the design team at GM who penned and had to sell the El Camino up the line. 

“You want to put a truck bed on a what??” So it’s like a truck … but a car?!” 😅

Defying convention, the El Camino lived (and sold!) for nearly 30 years, culminating in the ‘87 model seen here. Occasionally, radical and brave design ideas work.

And people are still clamoring for another one. But until that day comes, it might be best to take the steps Scott Chaney has taken with his, modernizing it with a buff LS6 V8 engine and performance aftermarket upgrades throughout. 

See more on @nittotire’s @drivingline.

I’ve seen a meme floating around recently of a post regarding a Tesla/EV car show, in which the OP claims something to the effect of Tesla owners being more passionate and loyal than owners of any other auto brand. 

Well, I covered that very #TeslaTakeover and @holleyhighvoltage (HHV) show by the @teslaownerssv group a cpl weeks ago in San Luis Obispo and wanted to offer some first-hand POV. 

First, superlatives are probably not the best idea when evaluating the passions of enthusiasts in an emerging segment against those with diehard loyalty, dedication and knowledge reaching back generations.

Second, there was some definite dedication to be felt among loyalists of Tesla and the various other makes present. But mostly what I felt was intrigue and interest. I liken it to what I experienced in the late 90s’ and early 00s’ import shows: young, novice enthusiasts interested in learning and unlocking the potential of a new thing. 

In that vane of thinking, the HHV portion of festivities was legit by any enthusiasts’ standards. The only three EV-converted vehicles I saw were in the AEM booth, and the performance driving that took place at nearby Santa Margarita Airport was definitely educational and entertaining. 

So ditch the memes on this one. Head over to @holleyperformance’s #MotorLife blog for a first-hand scoop of something we’ll only be seeing more of. 

#tesla #teslatakeover #HHV #rivian #lucid #porschetaycan  #model3 #teslamods #modelsplaid #plaid #EV #electriccar

Without a doubt, one of the most indelible memories I made at last weekend’s @holleylsfest was the moment stuntman @jim_york nosedived his LS-powered Buick Roadmaster wagon into flatground dirt at well over 60mph from nearly (or more than?) 20 feet high. 

“F—!” I thought. “He might be dead.”

Leading up to the jump, there was a lot of talk about how he was chasing a world record of some kind or another, and he spent a lot of time working with the ground crew to get the angle of the dirt jump to his liking. There was some semblance of a down-ramp, and I was expecting a *reasonably* civil landing.

But when he overshot the landing significantly (breaking the record easily), plummeted to the ground, and violently rolled several times over to a deadly silent crowd, I feared the worst. 

And then he emerged, high on horse-killing levels of adrenaline and sugar-free @redbull (last pic), and I felt relief like never before. 

Nicely done, sir. 👌

#holley #lsfest #lsf #lsfe #holleylsfest #lsx #gmls #carjump #jimyork #buickroadmaster #stationwagon #roadmaster

As a photographer, the dynamics of dirt and off-road driving are pretty cool. The exposed machinery of Ultra4 and rock-bouncing rigs. The mix of colors and texture presented by dirt, rocks and greenery. The excitement conveyed by leading explosions and trailing clouds of dirt.

Being inundated with all things automotive in my line of work, I’ve done a pretty terrible job of following the rise of automotive influencers. 

Names of brands and builders arise in conversation constantly, and my question is usually the same: “Who’s that?” 

But in that time, a lot of them have gone on to do some really cool stuff. Enter @gearsandgasoline and “the Bens.”

When filming a recent episode of @drivingline’s #DriverBattles series introduced me to these guys, I was immediately impressed. Ben Thorn’s EK Civic not only looked out of place at our filming location of @summitpointmp in WV (reminding me of the caliber of car I’d more commonly see at a track day in CA), he drove it uncommonly fast and consistently all day long for our shoot and time-attack competition.

Catch the full episode right now on the #DrivingLine YT channel, and watch out for a forthcoming post on Ben No. 2’s MRS lurking in the background of these shots. 💪

I love me a good, purpose-built car. And if the purpose for that build is partying with a bunch of your friends, sliding sideways around a race track near triple-digit speeds, I love that even more.

So, as you could imagine, I was pretty excited to shoot  @thedrewmclean’s 2JZ-powered E46 party wagon at @gridlifeofficial Midwest a while back. 

Some fun facts about this car: it’s painted, not vinyl wrapped; Drew built the car around the engine; and he even CAD-designed and laser cut (water cut?) his own suspension components and other bits. 

The car and the story are both pretty rad, and you can see more and read all about it on  @drivingline’s website right now.

When I was at @globaltimeattack last weekend, I made a quick story about feeling that either @riley_rsmotorsport’s Firebird or @mike_stanceworks’s Ferrari was my favorite car in attendance, but I wasn’t sure which one it was. I’m still not. 

First, both builds are works of art; way over the top, in contrast to the modus operandi of a stock-faithful engine and suspension upgrades most cars see. But in both cases, the level of modification isn’t “too much.” Everything works to elevate the performance and potential of both cars, and I remain eager to see just how fast they (and their owner/builder/drivers) will become. 

Second, can we realize how cool it is that a vintage Firebird and friggin’ Ferrari have become two of the hottest cars in the “import” scene and the sport of time-attack? I love it.

Another car that ranks way up there in the high-performance-work-of-art category for me (check out yesterday’s post) is @ca_preston’s awesome #Foxzilla Fox-body Mustang.

If Jules Verne or HG Wells had designed a car, it might look a lot like the 1913 Bugatti Type 22. 

After a diligent restoration, this particular one (of only a few surviving examples) remains in the care of Scottsdale-based Alan Travis, whose early-1900s collection of rare autos, motos, manuscripts, and assorted items of the era is unrivaled. 

With its handcrafted brass, copper, wood and glass adornments, this fully functional and regularly driven (and raced!) Bug might just be the crown jewel of the whole thing.

Something that frustrated me decades ago, as a young novice just getting into cars, was the amount of really great Ford compacts produced in Europe but never sold here — in Ford’s own home country! 

The legendary Ford Escort Cosworth and short-lived Merkur XR4Ti are prime examples. But before them, there was one such captive import that luckily slipped through: the mk1 Capri. 

Designed in England and built in Germany by Ford of Europe, the OG Capri brought an interesting blend of muscle-car style, small and nimble sportscar performance, and parts interchangeability to our shores. 

Decades later, drag racer James Meredith rediscovered and capitalized on  that elusive recipe in one built for dual street driving and drag racing, powered by a 550whp Coyote V8 engine and a surprisingly tame amount of supporting upgrades. 

Find the most recent feature on @holleyperformance’s #MotorLife blog for the full story, and more of my shots.
